<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1727,1861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1858" box="[151,296,1727,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Pachylophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,296,1727,1752]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Pachylophus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is defined by the combination of its chloropine wing venation (costa extending to apex of R4+5), its appreciably swollen hind femur, frontal triangle with only a single line of setae on either side, face lacking a median carina and the compactly black-haired arista situated preapically or apically on a postpedicel that is more or less reniform, though in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Deeming" authorityYear="2018" box="[425,554,1836,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Pachylophus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[425,554,1836,1861]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. mirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described here, it is more produced apically.
</paragraph>
